TY  - JOUR
AU  - Bagwell, Kyle
T1  - Introductory Price as a Signal of Cost in a Model of Repeat Business
PY  - 1987
Y1  - 1987/07/01
DO  - 10.2307/2297564
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 54
IS  - 3
SP  - 365
EP  - 384
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - A two-period game between firms and consumers is considered. Firms are privately informed about their individual costs, and consumers must pay a search cost in order to learn a firm's current price. Consumers thus have incentive to use introductory price as a signal of cost and, hence, second period price. Recent refinements of the sequential equilibrium concept are employed, and the resulting equilibria involve low introductory prices (introductory sales).
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2297564
ER  - 



